5000|$|Cross <b>compound</b> <b>locomotives</b> have a {{fundamental}} design issue, {{which is that}} if the HP cylinder is stopped [...] "on center", the locomotive cannot start. To resolve this, all practical cross <b>compound</b> <b>locomotives</b> have some form of starting valve, which allows admission of HP steam into the LP cylinder on starting. In some cases this is manually operated by the locomotive driver, while in other cases it is automatic; in the latter case the valve {{is often referred to as}} an [...] "intercepting valve". The primary difference between various forms of cross <b>compound</b> <b>locomotives</b> is in the design and operation of the intercepting valve.|$|R
